 University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Bilsby (Lincs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bilby","meanings":["English:","variant of   Bielby  .","shortened form of <b>Bilsby</b>, a habitational name from Bilsby in Lincolnshire, so named with the Old Norse personal name <i>Billi</i> + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. However, it is equally possible that <i>Bilsby</i> is an altered form of <i>Bilby</i>, with an intrusive <i>-s-</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Bilesby was born in 1400, in Lincolnshire, England, his father, Thomas Billesby, was 24 and his mother, Agnes Kirmond, was 24. He married Elizabeth Swynford about 1424, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1428, in his hometown, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1400–1428":"1400–1428","1417–1459":"1417–1459","1406–1428":"1406–1428","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1376–1430":"1376–1430","1376–1422":"1376–1422","1459":"1459","about 1428":"umbes 1428","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1399":"1399","about 1424":"umbes 1424","1376":"1376","1430":"1430","1470":"1470","1428":"1428","1406":"1406","1417":"1417","Bilsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Bilsby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","B